e who was fond of the drink or who made or sold mead. Compare   Meader  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Meadow","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a meadow, from Middle English <i>medewe</i>, <i>medu</i> (Old English <i>mǣdwe</i>, dative of <i>mǣd</i>). Compare   Mead   1."]},{"name":"Meads","meanings":["English: variant of   Mead  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Meade","meanings":["Irish: habitational name from <b>Midheach</b>, the Gaelic name of County Meath in Ireland. Its Anglicized forms are now indistinguishable from those of the English name   Mead  .","English: variant of   Mead  ."]},{"name":"Mather","meanings":["English:","occupational name for a mower or reaper of grass or hay, Old English <i>mǣthere</i>. Compare   Mead  ,   Mower  . Hay was formerly of great importance, not only as feed for animals in winter but also for bedding.","variant of   Mader  , reflecting an alternative pronunciation influenced by Old Norse <i>mathra</i> ‘madder (plant)’."]},{"name":"Meader","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>meder</i> ‘maker or seller of mead’. Compare   Mead   2."]},{"name":"Medd","meanings":["variant of   Mead   with shortening of the vowel.","possibly from Middle English <i>Medde</i>, a rare personal name of obscure origin.","English:"]},{"name":"Meddaugh","meanings":["Perhaps Irish, related to <b>Midheach</b> (see   Mead  )."]}]},{"name":"Stephen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephan","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , preserving the vowels of the Greek name."]},{"name":"Steven","meanings":["Variant of   Stephen  , reflecting the normal pronu